<TITLE> AL to sit with EC on electoral reform </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, October 22 (bdnews24.com)  The Awami League Monday decided to sit with the Election Commission for talks on electoral reforms. At a meeting of its central working committee, the AL set up a committee to do groundwork for the dialogue with the main election office. "We have agreed to sit with the Election Commission," acting AL president Zillur Rahman said in a press briefing after the meeting. The meeting held at the Awami League president's Dhanmondi office has been suspended until November 1. Some 43 members of the AL central working committee were present at the meeting, chaired by Zillur. Of the 73 members of the CWC two had died, one left the party informally and 11 including the president and the general secretary are in jail. Of the remaining 53 members, 10 were absent. Zohra Tajuddin, Sajeda Chowdhury, Tofail Ahmed, Suranjit Sengupta, Motia Chowdhury, Syed Ashraful Islam and Mukul Bose, among others, were present. "The party has decided to participate in the talks with the Election Commission responding to the invitation from the commission on November 4 as part of the series of talks with the political parties," Zillur said. Other leaders present at the meeting said the acting chairman had been tasked to form a committee for groundwork on the talks. Zillur demanded immediate withdrawal of restrictions on indoor politics throughout the country and an end to the state of emergency. He demanded Sheikh Hasina's release and vowed to continue legal battle for her freedom. He also sought release of the detained leaders of Awami League and its front organisations including party general secretary Abdul Jalil. The AL acting president also asked for quick completion of the trial of the assassination of independence leader Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and execution of the death sentence of the killers. He demanded of the government to bring the prices of essentials including rice, lentil, oil, atta and onion to the buying capacity of the common people. He suggested an initiative to control market prices by forming a committee. Zillur urged the government to ensure that the farmers get adequate fertiliser to get over the flood losses. He also demanded subsidy to agricultural inputs and farm loan on easy terms. He also asked for restoration of trade union right to the workers and release of the arrested teachers and students of Dhaka and Rajshahi universities on humanitarian grounds. He told journalists that the meeting approved a programme to observe the Jail Killing Day on November 3. bdnews24.
